<HL>
   Moody's Reviews
   Ratings of Three
   Japanese Banks
   ----
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C21
</SO>
<CO>
   MBK J.TKB J.LTC
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
</IN>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- Moody's Investors Service Inc. said it is
reviewing its ratings of the long-term debt of three Japanese
banks and some units for possible downgrading.
   The three banks are Mitsubishi Bank, rated triple-A; Tokai
Bank, rated double-A-2; and Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan,
or LTCB, also rated double-A-2. The respective Prime-1
ratings of the short-term debt of the banks aren't being
reviewed, Moody's said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mitsubishi and Tokai are Japanese "city banks,"
institutions with nationwide networks of branches. LTCB is
one of Japan's three designated long-term credit banks, which
are primarily wholesale lenders.
   Last month Moody's downgraded two Japanese city banks,
Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank and Fuji Bank, after placing them under
review in the spring. And still earlier this year Moody's
downgraded several trust banks, Mitsui Trust &amp; Banking Corp.,
Mitsubishi Trust &amp; Banking Corp. and Yasuda Trust &amp; Banking
Corp.
   Now put under review, Moody's said, are:
   -- Mitsubishi Bank's long-term deposits, senior debt and
standby letter-of-credit obligations and the senior debt of
the bank's guaranteed subsidiary, Mitsubishi Bank of
Australia Ltd.
   -- Tokai Bank's long-term deposits, senior debt and
letter-of-credit backed obligations.
   -- LTCB's long-term deposits, senior debt and long-term
standby letter-of-credit obligations, Long-Term Credit Bank
of Japan Finance N.V.'s senior debt and LTCB Australia Ltd.'s
long-term deposits.
   Moody's cited Mitsubishi Bank's "relatively weak core
profitability and competitive positions among its Japanese
peers" and "vulnerability to domestic asset-quality
deterioration."
   In reviewing Tokai Bank, Moody's will look at the lender's
quality of assets, especially "its domestic real
estate-related loan portfolio and its overseas credits," as
well as its core earnings and competitiveness, the rating
concern said.
   Meanwhile, LTCB's "weakening franchise as a wholesale
bank" as well as the bank's asset quality will come under
scrutiny, Moody's said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900918-0160
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900918-0160.
