<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
   Time Off: Diversions and Excursions Sept. 18-Oct. 1
</HL>
<DATE>
09/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A28
</SO>
<LP>
   ART
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Pierpont Morgan Library, New York: "Treasures of Eton
College Library: 550 Years of Collecting" -- More than 200
medieval and Renaissance manuscripts, rare books, drawings,
prints and objets d'art from England's Eton College.
Highlights include the only surviving copy of the earliest
English comedy, "Ralph Roister Doister," written in 1567 by a
headmaster at Eton; a large silver gilt model of the college
chapel presented to the school by King William IV; and
English drawings and watercolors by artists such as
Gainsborough and the portraitist Sir Thomas Lawrence. 29 East
36th St., Sept. 26-Nov. 25.
                                                                                                       

   Cleveland Museum of Art: "Reckoning With Winslow Homer:
His Late Paintings and Their Influence" -- About 50
paintings, many depicting the rocky coast of Maine, by Homer
(1836-1910) and other American artists influenced by him
(Edward Hopper, N.C. Wyeth, John Marin). 11150 East
Boulevard, Sept. 19-Nov. 18. The show then travels to the
Columbus Museum of Art, Dec. 16, 1990-Feb. 10, 1991; and the
Corcoran Gallery of Art, Washington, D.C., March 16-May 12,
1991.
                                                                                                       

   Arthur M. Sackler Gallery, Smithsonian Institution:
"Antoin Sevruguin: Photographs of Iran" -- More than 25
photos by this commercial photographer of Armenian and
Russian descent who worked in Tehran between the 1880s and
the 1920s. His patrons included at least two rulers of the
Qajar dynasty (1779-1924), as well as wealthy Iranians,
foreign scholars and tourists. In subject matter and
composition, many of the works closely resemble 16th- and
17th-century Persian paintings and drawings. 1050
Independence Ave., Sept. 30, 1990-May 26, 1991.
                                                                                                       

   The Jewish Museum, New York: "A Day in the Warsaw Ghetto"
-- On Sept. 19, 1941, German Army Sgt. Heinz Jost spent his
birthday taking pictures inside the ghetto, where
half-a-million Polish Jews were forcibly contained. Never
before exhibited in the U.S., the 85 photographs document
street scenes inside the ghetto, where some 85,000 people
died "natural" deaths from starvation and illness. Diary
excerpts accompany the photographs. On view here till Nov. 1
(1109 Fifth Ave.), the exhibition will tour the country
through March 1995.
                                                                                                       

   Museum of Modern Art, New York: "Lady Hawarden, Victorian
Photographer" -- The dreamy young women captured in a variety
of poses and costumes in these 50 albumen-silver prints are
the photographer's daughters. Taken in family homes in London
and Ireland, the photographs seem like fragments from a lost
world. 11 West 53rd Street, till Oct. 9.
                                                                                                       

   FILM
                                                                                                       

   New York Film Festival: This year's 2 1/2-week movie
marathon offers scores of films from 14 countries. There's
already a buzz about the opening attraction, "Miller's
Crossing," a gangster film by Joel and Ethan Coen ("Raising
Arizona") starring Gabriel Byrne and Albert Finney. Other
highlights include two black comedies from Finland's Aki
Kaurismaki, a documentary about music man Quincy Jones, and
new offerings from French auteurs Jean-Luc Godard and Eric
Rohmer. Alice Tully Hall, Lincoln Center, 65th and Broadway.
Sept. 21-Oct. 7. (212) 362-1911.
                                                                                                       

   The 14th annual Margaret Mead Film Festival presents 45
documentary films on such diverse topics as sex, love and
marriage in Ethiopia; the relationships between women and
Japanese soldiers stationed in Papua New Guinea during World
War II; and the difficulties of shooting a major Western
motion picture in China. New Yorkers and others familiar with
or curious about the Big Apple shouldn't miss "Outrageous
Taxi Stories," a short film by Joe Berlinger featuring
taxi-drivers' bizarre tales as well as one really outrageous
story told by a female passenger. Central Park West at 79th
Street, Sept. 2427. Screenings 6:30-10:30 nightly; ticket
sales begin at 5 p.m. (212) 769-5305.
                                                                                                       

   MUSIC
                                                                                                       

   Metropolitan Opera: The season opens Sept. 24 with Mirella
Freni and Placido Domingo in "La Boheme" and continues in its
traditional way offering "Der Rosenkavalier" on the 25th,
"Rigoletto" on the 26th and "Don Giovanni" on the 27th.
Debuts include Guido Ajmone-Marsan leading June Anderson in
"Rigoletto," and mezzo Anne Sofie von Otter, who sings the
rosebearing sex toy, Octavian, in a revival of the Strauss
comedy conducted by Carlos Kleiber. Lincoln Center. (212)
799-3100.
                                                                                                       

   New York City Opera: Arnold Schoenberg's big work for
chorus, soloists and several naked virgins, "Moses und Aron,"
receives its first New York staging in sets by Achim Freyer,
with Hans Neugebauer directing and the company's general
director, Christopher Keene, in the pit. Lincoln Center.
Sept. 22, 27; Oct. 3, 6, 10, 12. (212) 870-5570.
                                                                                                       

   Seattle Opera: The company opens its fall season with a
revival of that old dog and pony show, "Cavalleria
Rusticana," coupled, for a curious change of pace, not with
"I Pagliacci" but a new production of Puccini's "Gianni
Schicchi" directed by Francesca Zambello and designed by
Bruno Schwengl. Bolshoi soprano Makvala Kasrashvilli sings
Santuzza; tenor James Hoback is the feckless Turridu. Julian
Patrick portrays the wily Schicchi and Cal Stewart Kellogg
conducts. Seattle Opera House. Sept. 22, 23, 26, 28, 29; Oct.
3. (206) 443-3299.
                                                                                                       

   Bill Bruford's Earthworks: One of pop's premier drummers
and his trio play the lustrous jazz fusion showcased on their
album "Dig?" (Editions EG). Dates include: Oberlin, Ohio
(Oberlin College), Sept. 28; Chicago (Park West), Sept. 30;
Pittsburgh (The Graffiti), Oct. 1; Cambridge, Mass.
(Nightshade), Oct. 3; New York City (Bottom Line), Oct. 4-5;
Philadelphia (Chestnut Cabaret), Oct. 10; Washington (Bayou),
Oct. 11; Sacramento, Calif. (Crest Theater), Oct. 14; San
Francisco (Great American Music Hall), Oct. 17; San Diego
(Bacchanal), Oct. 20.
</TEXT>
