BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report.
                                                                                                       

                          CORPORATE
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Champion International Corp. -- $150 million of 9.65%
notes due Oct. 1, 1995, priced at par. The noncallable notes
were priced at a spread of 114 basis points above the
Treasury's five-year note. Rated Baa-1 by Moody's Investors
Service Inc. and triple-B by Standard &amp; Poor's Corp., the
issue will be sold through underwriters led by Goldman Sachs
&amp; Co.
   World Savings &amp; Loan Association -- $100 million of 10.25%
subordinated notes due Oct. 1, 1997, priced at par to yield
10.25%. The noncallable notes were priced at 150 basis points
above the Treasury's seven-year note. Rated single-A2 by
Moody's and single-A-minus by S&amp;P, the issue will be sold
through underwriters led by Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
World Savings &amp; Loan is a unit of Golden West Financial Corp.
                                                                                                       

                          MUNICIPAL
                                                                                                       

   New York State Urban Development Corp. -- $228.1 million
of correctional capital facilities revenue bonds, Series 1,
due Jan. 1, 1992-2003, 2016 and 2020, tentatively priced by a
Goldman Sachs &amp; Co. group to yield from 6.50% in 1992 to
8.00% in 2016. Current interest serial bonds are priced to
yield from 6.50% in 1992 to 7.50% in 2003. There are $118.2
million of 7.75% term bonds priced at 97.29 to yield 8.00% in
2016 and $66 million of 7.50% term bonds priced at 97.67 to
yield 7.70% in 2020. Ratings of single-A/triple-B-plus are
expected.
   Rhode Island Housing and Mortgage Financial Corp. --
$125.8 million of home ownership opportunity bonds, Series
3-A due Oct. 1, 2010 and 2016, and Series 3-B due April 1 and
Oct. 1, 1992-2000, 2019 and 2022, priced by a Goldman, Sachs
&amp; Co. group to yield from 6.40% in 1992 to 8.05% in 2022.
Series 3-A consists of $43.8 million of bonds. There are
$20.9 million of 7.80% term bonds priced at par due in 2010
and $22.8 million of 7.85% term bonds priced at par due in
2016. Series 3-B consists of $82 million of bonds. Current
interest serial bonds are priced at par to yield from 6.40%
in 1992 to 7.25% in 2000. There are $40 million of tender
option bonds due in 2019 that are not formally reoffered and
$34.8 million of 8.05% term bonds priced at par due in 2022.
Interest on the Series 3-B bonds will be treated as a
preference item in calculating the federal alternative
minimum tax that may be imposed on certain investors.
Interest on the Series 3-A bonds will not be subject to the
tax. Ratings of single-A-1/ double-A-plus are expected.
                                                                                                       

                          MORTGAGES
                                                                                                       

   Federal National Mortgage Association -- $300.2 million of
Remic mortgage securities offered in 11 classes by Bear,
Stearns &amp; Co. The offering, Series 1990-127, is backed by
Fannie Mae 10% securities with a weighted average coupon rate
of 10.625% and weighted average remaining term to maturity of
29.58 years.
   Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. -- $300 million of Remic
mortgage securities offered in 10 classes by Merrill Lynch
Capital Markets. The offering, Series FHLMC Gold 1007, is
backed by Freddie Mac 10 1/2% gold participation certificates
with a weighted average coupon rate of 11.25% and weighted
average remaining term to maturity of 28.5 years. Price and
yield data weren't immediately available.
                                                                                                       

                          EUROBONDS
                                                                                                       

   ICI (Australian) Finance Ltd (U.K. parent) -- 60 million
Australian dollars of 14 1/4% Eurobonds due Oct. 22, 1993,
issue price 101 1/2, via Hambros Bank Ltd. Guarantor ICI
(Australia) Ltd. Fees 1 1/2.
   Czechoslovakian Trade Bank (Czechoslovakia) -- 350 million
marks of 10% bonds due Oct. 5, 1995, priced at 101 to yield
9.73%, via Deutby Statnibank Ceskoslovenska, the state
central bank. Fees 2.
</TEXT>
