<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
09/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   GM AND THE UAW AGREED on a three-year contract. The terms
call for the automaker to spend as much as $4 billion to
sweeten a range of job and income security programs. The
agreement imposes restrictions on GM's ability to close
plants but apparently doesn't require the company to find
work for some 30,000 GM union members laid off during the
past three years.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A United Airlines union group seeking to buy United's
parent, UAL, plans to meet with banks this week about a new
offer of $175 to $180 a share, or $3.82 billion to $3.92
billion, said people familiar with the deal.
   ---
   The G-7 nations' finance ministers and central bankers
will meet in Washington Saturday to discuss higher oil
prices, recent interest rate rises, and the decline in the
dollar.
   ---
   Charles Keating is to be arraigned today on criminal fraud
charges in a California state court. The charges are said to
include allegations of fraudulent sales of debentures through
the now-collapsed Lincoln S&amp;L.
   ---
   Crude oil prices soared to records on the New York
Mercantile Exchange following events that pointed up the
likelihood of a war in the Middle East and possible supply
disrup tions. The October crude contract ended $1.87 a barrel
higher at $33.63.
   ---
   Budget negotiators continued to haggle over what price the
Democrats would demand for a cut in the capital-gains tax,
and Bush renewed his call for such a reduction.
   ---
   Colonial Realty is the target of efforts by six banks to
force the company into involuntary bankruptcy-court
liquidation. Colonial's financial distress raises the
possibility of losses to the many individual investors in its
real-estate partnerships.
   ---
   U.S. bankers are concerned that economic weakness will
lead to increased defaults on credit-card debt.
   ---
   Italy's Pirelli proposed to West Germany's Continental
that they merge their tire businesses to challenge France's
Michelin, America's Goodyear and Japan's Bridgestone.
   ---
   U.S. bank regulators would be allowed to raise deposit
insurance premiums to whatever levels they feel necessary
under a bill passed by the House. Separately, bank regulators
settled a dispute over capital levels.
   ---
   NCR is expected to unveil today a redesign of its product
line based on Intel's computer chips and software.
   ---
   Sears debt was downgraded by Moody's, which lowered
ratings on about $6.9 billion of the company's securities.
The ratings agency said a continuing drop in consumer spend
ing will hamper the company's efforts to boost merchandising
results.
   ---
   The Japanese stock market is the focus of new futures and
options offered by three major U.S. exchanges.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 110,600,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2567.33, up 3.22; transportation 887.94, off 1.48; utilities
199.89, up 0.69.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Brothers Treasury index 3329.12,
off 9.80.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 132.74, up 0.45; spot
index 129.35, up 0.28.
   Dollar: 136.55 yen, off 0.40; 1.5480 marks, off 0.023.
