WSJ900918-0003
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900918-0003.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   S&amp;L Bailout Agency
   Cancels the Auction
   Of Thrift Properties
</HL>
<DATE>
09/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal savings and loan bailout
officials said Monday they were canceling the much-promoted
international satellite auction of million-dollar properties
inherited from bankrupt savings and loans.
   L. William Seidman, chairman of the Resolution Trust
Corp., said the auction was canceled after the Auction Co. of
America, which the agency had hired, did not contribute to a
joint fund promoting the event.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "The group we contracted with couldn't fulfill their end
of the deal," Mr. Seidman said in a telephone interview.
   Jim Gall, chairman of the Miami-based Auction Co. of
America, disputed Mr. Seidman and accused the bailout agency
of bungling the auction. He said the firm has spent nearly $2
million over four months to prepare for the event, about what
it was obligated to spend.
   The auction was to be held Nov. 15 in Dallas with
satellite hookups to bidders in nine other U.S. cities as
well as Tokyo and London.
   The RTC had hoped to sell 71 properties valued at $300
million. The auction was a centerpiece for what the agency
had billed as its "great fall inventory clearance sale" aimed
at drastically slimming its ballooning inventory of S&amp;L
assets.
   "We hope to start over. . . . It's going to slow us up a
little but, but I don't think it's a major blow," Mr. Seidman
said.
   Mr. Gall faulted the RTC for failing to set minimum prices
for the properties and for withdrawing three properties from
the auction list and selling them using other methods.
   Mr. Gall said potential buyers must have some assurance
the properties will remain on the auction list or they will
be unwilling to spend thousands of dollars on the
environmental, engineering and appraisal reports needed to
offer an intelligent bid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900918-0002
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900918-0002.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   New York Post Union
   Votes to Accept Cuts
</HL>
<DATE>
09/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR TRB
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- The Newspaper Guild voted overwhelmingly to
accept New York Post owner Peter S. Kalikow's proposal of
wage-and-benefit cuts to keep the 189-year-old tabloid in
business.
   After a loud and emotional meeting that lasted for two
hours, Guild members, made up largely of editors, reporters
and advertising staff, voted 242-45 to approve concessions,
which call for a four-day workweek, a 20% cut in salary and
the elimination of dozens of jobs. Ten other newspaper unions
are expected to approve similar cuts.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   If the proposal had been rejected, Mr. Kalikow vowed to
shut down the paper with a final edition for today. Folding
the paper would have put 960 people out of work. Mr. Kalikow
has sought $27 million in cost cuts so the paper can break
even in 1990.
   Later this week, Mr. Kalikow and the unions are expected
to sign a new three-year contract. "Three years, for the Post
that's a long time," said Paul Tharp, a Post reporter after
emerging from the union hall in Manhattan.
   Though many union members said they were against cutting
their own pay and workweek, they were swayed by a last-minute
sweetener by Mr. Kalikow to boost severance pay for those who
agree to resign. At the Guild meeting, several members spoke
out saying they would approve the contract but they would
take the buyout. Mr. Kalikow has also promised the unions 20%
of the company's stock and a representative on the board.
   The settlement at the Post is expected to put pressure on
Tribune Co.'s Daily News, which is in the midst of stalled
and bitter negotiations with its unions. The Daily News,
however, is asking its unions for extensive changes in hiring
and operations, whereas Mr. Kalikow was looking only to cut
costs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900918-0001
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900918-0001.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Abreast of the Market:
   Stocks End Mixed in Slow Trading;
   Oil-Price Rise Boosts Energy Issues
   ----
   By David Wilson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C2
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Stock prices closed mixed in sluggish trading,
but ended the session on an upswing as another surge in the
price of oil rekindled buying interest in the energy sector.
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 3.22 to 2567.33, but
gains in Exxon, Chevron and Texaco more than accounted for
the advance; the performance of the three oil stocks lifted
the average by nearly six points.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Broader market indexes also posted modest gains. Standard
&amp; Poor's 500-Stock Index went up 0.94 to 317.77, the New York
Stock Exchange Composite Index rose 0.47 to 174.62 and the
Dow Jones Equity Market Index added 0.79 to 294.40.
   But declining issues led advancers on the Big Board by 768
to 681, and traders said the market remained plagued by
uncertainty regarding the Persian Gulf situation and the
deficit-reduction talks.
   "Nobody wants to make any commitments for fear that
they're going to be wrong tomorrow," said James C. Andrews,
first vice president in charge of institutional trading at
Janney Montgomery Scott in Philadelphia.
   Only 110,600,000 shares were traded, down from 133,390,000
shares Friday. Concerns about today's reports on the August
consumer price index and the July trade deficit also kept
investors out of the market, traders said.
   Both reports are expected to reflect the impact of higher
oil prices, even though the July trade data was collected
before Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
   The CPI is expected to show an increase of 0.8%, with
prices excluding food and energy up 0.4%, according to a
consensus of economists polled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report. The July trade deficit is expected to widen to $7.3
billion from $5.1 billion in June, with a rise in oil imports
accounting for the move.
   Although analysts have cited oil prices as a key influence
on the market recently, stocks declined only briefly in the
latest session as crude-oil futures surged to the highest
levels in New York trading since being introduced in 1983.
October futures ended the session at $33.63 a barrel, up
$1.87.
   Jon Groveman, president of Ladenburg, Thalmann &amp; Co., said
the previous surges in oil prices blunted the impact of the
latest advance on the market. "A lot of people who wanted to
react to that {rally} already have done so," Mr. Groveman
says.
   Scattered bargain-hunting by institutional investors
helped the market recover its initial losses, traders said.
Stocks then proceeded to spend most of the session drifting
within tight trading ranges; buying in the final hour pushed
prices to session highs.
   Chevron advanced 1 3/4 to 77 5/8, while Texaco rose 7/8 to
65 3/8 and Exxon gained 1/4 to 51 5/8. Among other oil
stocks, Mobil added 1 to 66 1/2, Amoco added 1 1/8 to 58 3/8,
Unocal rose 1 to 33 1/4 and Atlantic Richfield climbed 1 3/4
to 141 5/8. Within the oilfield-services sector, Halliburton
rallied 1 1/4 to 55 7/8, Schlumberger went up 1/4 to 66 1/2
and Parker Drilling jumped 3/4 to 8 3/4.
   Similarly, precious-metals stocks took their direction
from gold prices; October gold futures rose $4.20 an ounce,
to $390.60 in New York trading. Homestake Mining went up 5/8
to 20 1/2, Newmont Mining rose 7/8 to 43 7/8 and Placer Dome
added 1/4 to 17 3/8.
   Digital Equipment, which fell 9 7/8 last week as the
company cautioned against expecting any quick turnaround in
its fortunes, rebounded 1/4 to 56 5/8 in composite trading of
1.6 million shares. But Digital traded as low as 54 during
the session, and The Wall Street Journal reported in
yesterday's "Heard on the Street" column that few analysts
are willing to bet it has hit bottom.
   International Business Machines gained 3/4 to 105 1/8. IBM
and Microsoft are expected to realign some of their
responsibilities for the development of the OS/2 operating
system for personal computers, which has flopped so far, the
Journal reported.
   Unisys went down 1/4 to 7 7/8 in active trading, and other
key technology stocks also headed lower. Hewlett-Packard
dropped 3/8 to 32 3/4, Compaq Computer dipped 1/2 to 43 5/8,
Cray Research slipped 3/4 to 34 5/8 and Control Data lost 7/8
to 11 5/8.
   UAL slipped 1 5/8 to 97 3/8. A group of unions at its
United Airlines unit is likely to abandon its most recent
buy-out offer -- valued at $201 a share, or $4.38 billion --
and may submit another, lower bid, the Journal reported.
   McDonnell Douglas fell 1 7/8 to 50. Smith Barney, Harris
Upham downgraded its investment rating on the stock to
"avoid" from "hold."
   American Home Products gained 3/4 to 48. As expected, the
company reached an agreement to help MicroGeneSys in
developing VaxSyn HIV-1, an experimental AIDS vaccine. Of
three vaccines now under intense study, VaxSyn has undergone
the most advanced human tests.
   U.S. Surgical jumped 2 5/8 to 56 1/2. Salomon Brothers
upgraded its rating on the stock, which the firm expects to
outperform the market, and increased its earnings estimates
for 1990, 1991 and 1992 by 10 cents, 20 cents and 70 cents a
share -- to $1.65, $2.10 and $3, respectively.
   Capital Holding rose 1/4 to 35. The company said it plans
to repurchase up to two million common shares, including
about 550,000 shares to be bought through its employee
pension fund.
   Apple Bancorp, which dropped its opposition to a
$38-a-share takeover bid from New York real estate investor
Stanley Stahl, tacked on 3/8 to 33 1/8. The bank holding
company said it is now taking a neutral position on the
offer.
   Paired certificates of Hotel Investors Trust and Hotel
Investors Corp. gained 5/8 to 3 1/2. First West Capital is
offering $5 each for the securities in a takeover offer.
   The American Stock Exchange Market Value Index rose 0.26
to 321.71. Volume totaled 9,810,000 shares.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
